This file describes features that are not yet implemented, and bugs that are
not yet fixed. Items are grouped by priority for production readiness.

=== Known bugs ===

(none currently — bug#239590 host-LAN-loopback rejection FIXED in 0.8.39)

=== High priority — blocking production use ===

(High-priority items above are now complete; the next batch is
operational quality.)

=== Medium priority — operational quality ===

* (feature, partial) `crate update TARGET --pkg-only` — in-place
  pkg upgrade inside a running jail. *Shipped in 0.8.41.* Runs
  `pkg upgrade [-n] [-y]` via jexec(8); jail keeps running.
  Full base-system update remains open: it would need a
  snapshot-and-rollback dance because /usr/lib, /usr/sbin, /lib
  are in use by the jail's running processes. Tracked as a
  separate larger item.

* (feature) Hub scheduling — automatic container placement on the
  least-loaded host. *Shipped end-to-end* — endpoint in 0.8.40
  (`GET /api/v1/scheduling/least-loaded[?current=<name>]`),
  CLI helper in 0.8.43 (`crate-hub schedule <jail> --from
  <host:port> --from-token-file <p> --to-token-file <p>
  [--current <name>] [--hub-url <url>] [--dry-run]`). Anti-flap
  (within 10% of best -> keep current) on both the endpoint and
  the CLI exit-early path.

=== Out of scope (separate repository) ===

* Admin/dashboard UI for the datacenter view. The hub already
  exposes /api/v1/{nodes,datacenters,aggregate,containers} and
  the per-node crated daemon owns the F2 mutating surface
  (start/stop/restart/destroy, snapshot CRUD, export/import,
  console-over-WS, stats SSE). A richer admin SPA — DC create/
  rename, drag-drop node moves, per-DC quotas, log/console
  attach — will live in its own repository so the frontend can
  pick its own framework, build pipeline, and release cadence
  without dragging the C++ side along. The minimal vanilla-JS
  dashboard in hub/web/ stays as a built-in fallback for
  tokenless local monitoring.

=== Low priority — future enhancements (architectural) ===

These items each represent multi-week / multi-release work. Not
suitable for one-shot sprints; need their own design pass.

* (feature) Rootless containers — multi-week refactor to remove
  the setuid root bit from `crate(1)` and delegate privileged
  operations to a daemon (`crated`).

  Note on framing: the current setuid root model is NOT "leaky".
  It has the expected hardening for a 2026 setuid binary —
  env-sanitization at startup (CWE-426 + CWE-250 explicitly
  cited in cli/main.cpp:42-69), absolute paths via CRATE_PATH_*
  for every external binary, all execs go through execv with
  explicit argv (no shell expansion, no system()/popen()
  anywhere), pure-module validators on every operator-supplied
  string (paths, iface names, datasets, ports, RCTL keys), and
  audit logging of every mutating command. Single-tenant
  homelab + single-tenant prod use cases are well-served.

  Why rootless still matters:
    - blast-radius reduction on hypothetical 3rd-party CVE
      (yaml-cpp, libssl, tar) — exploit gets caller UID, not root
    - multi-tenant safety — Alice can't `crate run` Bob's jail
      (today the binary trusts whoever invokes it; filesystem
      perms on /var/run/crate/ don't scope per-user)
    - compliance "no setuid root binaries on host" policies

  Foundations already in tree:
    0.6.4   WebSocket console — separate listener (pattern for
            replacing cpp-httplib with a hand-rolled accept loop)
    0.7.11  Control sockets with getpeereid + per-group access
            (per-operator unix sockets exist; multi-tenant gate
            for control plane works today)
    0.7.14  Capsicum sandbox (per-fd cap_rights_limit)
    0.8.19  Filesystem-perm gate on main socket
            (listen.unix_owner / unix_group / unix_mode)
    0.8.21  Spec registry {name -> abs-path} so daemon knows
            what to start without operator re-supplying -f
    0.8.23  DrmSession::probeDevice via libseat — rootless DRM
            access foundation
    0.8.24  cap_syslog dual-write — audit resilient to a future
            cap_enter() of crated

  What the refactor needs:
    - Privileged daemon protocol: extend control sockets for
      the full operation set (create_jail, mount, set_rctl,
      attach_zfs, configure_iface, add_pf_rule, add_ipfw_rule).
      Per-verb argv validation on the daemon side — never trust
      caller input. ~3-5 days.
    - lib/run.cpp split (~1700 LOC currently) into "needs root"
      → IPC to crated, and "doesn't" → inline. Big refactor;
      ~1 week.
    - Per-user resource namespacing:
        * jail name prefix: <user>-<jailname>
        * ZFS dataset prefix: per-user via crated.conf ACL
        * Network pool sub-CIDR per user
          (alice: 10.66.1.0/24, bob: 10.66.2.0/24, …)
        * RCTL accounting groups per UID
        * /var/run/crate/<uid>/ for per-user lease + log files
      ~1 week.
    - Setuid bit removal in Makefile install target
      (-m 0755 instead of 04755). Migration path for legacy
      setuid deployments — operator runs crated and switches
      gradually.
    - Documentation: docs/rootless-migration.md, crated.8 update,
      multi-tenant operator config example. ~3-5 days.
    - Tests for security boundaries (alice can't see bob's jails;
      ZFS dataset escape attempts; pool-exhaustion DoS;
      per-user audit filtering). ~1 week.

  Estimated total: 4-6 weeks of focused work, splittable into
  ~10 point releases (0.9.0 through 0.9.9, 1.0.0 to remove the
  setuid bit by default). NOT a one-shot sprint.

  Trigger: tracked. Not a current priority. Becomes urgent when
  one of:
    - a real multi-tenant operator request lands
    - a compliance audit requires "no setuid root binaries"
    - a high-severity CVE in a linked library makes the
      blast-radius story acute

* (feature) Layered images — ZFS-based layering through clones
  instead of monolithic .crate archives. Touches `crate create`,
  `crate run`, `crate import`, `crate export` simultaneously —
  the on-disk archive format becomes a manifest pointing at
  multiple parent snapshots. Spec format extension required.

* (security) True getpeereid(2)-based unix-socket auth in crated.
  *Partial mitigation shipped in 0.8.19* — operators can now
  scope `/var/run/crate/crated.sock` access via filesystem perms
  (`listen.unix_owner / unix_group / unix_mode` in crated.conf).
  That's group-based access control via the OS; sufficient for
  the typical "same-host operator group" model.
  The deeper getpeereid fix needs the underlying connection fd
  which cpp-httplib doesn't expose — requires either forking
  httplib's accept loop or replacing the unix-socket transport
  with a hand-rolled listener (similar to how WebSocket console
  got its own listener in 0.6.4 and control sockets got theirs
  in 0.7.11). Tracked for a future privsep refactor sprint.

